<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Tamarix</i> <i>ramosissima</i> or another <i>Tamarix</i> species is dominant in the shrub canopy. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Populus</i> <i>fremontii</i> or <i>Salix</i> spp. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 8 m; canopy is continuous or open. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Tamarix</i> spp. > 3% absolute cover and > 60% relative cover compared to other microphyllous trees or shrubs (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Tamarix</i> spp. > 60% relative cover in the shrub canopy with minor presence of native species (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Tamarix</i> spp. > 60% relative cover in the shrub or low tree canopy (Thomas et al. 2004, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Tamarix</i> spp. > 75% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Evens and San 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Tamarix</i> spp. > 75% relative cover in the shrub canopy. Riparian woodland species can be emergent to shrub layer with cover < 5% (Menke and Johnson 2016)</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Arroyo margins, lake margins, ditches, washes, rivers, and other watercourses. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Tamarix parviflora</i> and <i>T. ramosissima</i> as a FAC plant. </div>
</div>

        
