<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> The genus <i>Tamarix </i>involves some 60 African and Eurasian species. Gaskin (2006; see the note at the Jepson Online Interchange http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/ jepsonmanual/review/index) considers that five species grow in California: <i>T. aphylla, T. chinensis, T. gallica, T. parviflora, </i>and <i>T. ramosissima. </i>All are invasive to some degree (DiTomaso and Healy 2007, Lovich 2000). <br/>
<br/>
These species possess eco-physiological characteristics that make them remarkably formidable as invasive plants. They are long-lived shrubs or trees with extensive and deep root systems. They consume large quantities of water, possibly more than any other woody species in similar habitats, because they can obtain water at very low water potentials and have very high water-use efficiencies. They are highly tolerant of alkaline and saline habitats and can concentrate salts in their leaves. They have an advantage over native phreatophytes (e.g., cottonwoods and willows) in areas where salt levels are elevated or water tables depressed. Seeds germinate on saturated soil or while afloat; seedling establishment requires moist soil. Once established, they resist desiccation. Plants sprout from root crowns, and freshly detached stems will root in moist soil. They are unpalatable to livestock and wildlife. Identification at the specific level is difficult; congeners hybridize, and their ecologies are similar (Carpenter 2005, DiTomaso and Healy 2007, Lovich 2000). <br/>
<br/>
Tamarisk species have invaded the native vegetation in riparian areas where they develop dense, monospecific stands across floodplains, wetlands, and lake margins throughout the western United States. <i>T. parviflora, </i>smallflower tamarisk, has a Cal-IPC rank of High and CDFA rank B. It is a deciduous shrub to 5 m tall with small pink flowers, each with four sepals and petals. <i>T. ramosissima, </i>saltcedar, has a Cal-IPC rank of High and CDFA rank B. It is a deciduous shrub or tree to 8 m tall with white to pink flowers, each with four sepals and petals. <i>T. aphylla, </i>athel, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited. It is a semi-evergreen or evergreen tree to 12 m tall with white to pale pink flowers, each with five sepals and petals. The leaves are scales that completely sheath the twigs, making them appear jointed. <i>T. chinensis </i>is a CDFA rank B. It is a shrub to 8 m tall with flower parts in fours. The leaves are awl-like <i>. T. gallica, </i>French tamarisk, is a CDFA rank B. It is a shub or tree to 5 m tall with flower parts in fives. The leaves are awl-like. See DiTomaso and Healy (2007) for further details. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
