    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ah). Regional experts noted that in the Salinas River watershed populations were increasing and not under management (Cal-IPC, 2018+)</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac-e, Ag, Aj-k). Stands were surveyed around streams in the Panoche Hills, along Los Gatos Creek and are known to be occasional along several streams in the section, such as along San Benito and Salinas rivers.  There are also stands along the Cuyama River and tributaries in the Caliente Range (VegCAMP, 2010).</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Plants grow in fan palm oases and in several wetlands in the section, including along washes in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b). Concerted efforts over the last 20 years to remove stands in the state park have resulted in substantial reductions in acreage. There are many stands along the eastern edge of the Salton Sea and following the East Highline Canal.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands are common along Stony Creek, Cache Creek, and other creeks in the section; they occur occasionally along the main stems of the Sacramento and San Joaquin rivers. They are also common along the canals associated with the Kern River (VegCAMP, 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ai). Regional experts noted that near Shasta Lake populations were decreasing (Cal-IPC, 2018+)</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ab-d, Af-i, Al-p). Stands occur along the Mojave River and at many springs throughout the section with <i>Senegalia greggii, Ambrosia salsola, Atriplex </i>spp.<i>, Populus fremontii, </i>or <i>Salix </i>spp. mixing with the tamarisk (Thomas et al. 2004).   Stands are have also been found at Joshua Tree National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005).They are also found along the Colorado River.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb, Bf). Regional experts noted that around streams near Ukiah and in northeast Napa County populations were decreasing (Cal-IPC, 2018+)</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). Stands occur throughout the section at low elevations, especially along Cache Creek in Colusa and Yolo Cos.; and Bear Creek in Napa County (Thorne et al, 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-s). Stands are found along Cache Creek and other streams surrounding Tehachapi (VegCAMP, 2015a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands are sporadic along several foothill streams (Menke et al. 2011).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands are wide-ranging along the Colorado River and along other smaller stream courses and springs (Menke et al. 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc). <i>Tamarix </i>spp. has been sampled in Death Valley NP, near Salt Lake</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-g, Bi-j). Stands exist in the Los Angeles Basin along several creeks and rivers and repeatedly in disturbed habitats, such as along fluctuating lake margins and aqueducts. They also occur as dense stands in riparian habitats in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005), central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005), and along the Santa Clara River (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007) with <i>Baccharis salicifolia, Salix gooddingii, S. lasiolepis, </i>and various non-native plants including <i>Arundo donax.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bj-l, Bn, Bp). Stands have been found along the San Dieguito River and tributaries, near Lake Matthews outside Perris, in the Oak Grove Valley north of Warner Springs. <i>Tamarix</i> spp. Have been seen along streams and washes, and are known from regional experts to be present and increasing in the streams around Ontario  (Cal-IPC, 2018+).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Tamarisk species are among the most invasive, widely distributed, and troublesome non-natives to infest the state’s wetlands. Multiple, interacting factors facilitate tamarisk invasion, including intentional planting for erosion control and windbreaks; land conversion to agriculture; reduced flood frequencies after damming rivers; changing and stabilizing water flows, times, and rates downstream from reservoirs; and increased salinity levels in the rivers from evaporation in the reservoirs (Everitt 1980). Tamarisk vigorously sprouts after fire, and plants increase flowering and seed production after fire. Mixed riparian stands often change to tamarisk-dominated stands after fires (Zouhar 2003b, Brooks and Minnich 2006). 

Active programs to remove tamarisk are ongoing in the state (Lovich 2000). Discouraging tamarisk establishment by biological and mechanical control is the most effective method of control. Once established in large stands, control and eradication efforts are difficult and costly; many managers recommend integrated management approaches (Carpenter 2005, Lovich 2000, Zouhar 2003b). </div>
</div>

    

    

